#Text=Thousands protest over alleged Russian election fraud
#Text=Sunday , December 11 , 2011
#Text=Logo of the United Russia political party .
#Text=Image : Единая Россия .

#Text=Tens of thousands protested yesterday in Bolotnaya Square , Moscow over allegations of election fraud in parliamentary elections won by United Russia , the ruling political party , led by current Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin .

#Text=The exact number of protesters present is unknown ; estimates for the Moscow protest vary from twenty thousand to one hundred thousand , and rallies on a more minor scale also took place in other Russian cities — including Saint Petersburg .
#Text=Voice of America ( VoA ) reported the demonstrations as the largest pro-democracy protests since Vladimir Putin came to power eleven years ago .
#Text=Other reports describe the demonstrations as the greatest since the dissolution of the Soviet Union .
#Text=Police estimated that ten thousand people were present at demonstrations in St. Petersburg .
#Text=Corruption and a rejection of Putin were the most commonly-cited grievances from questioned protesters .
#Text=Opposition leader Evgenia Chirikova told VoA the protests were in favour of fresh elections , and the release of political prisoners .
#Text=During the demonstrations , protesters chanted " [ p]olice , part of the people " at the riot police .
#Text=Echo of Moscow host Alexei Venediktov described the protesters as " the new generation , the Putin generation " .
#Text=These people " voted , had their votes stolen , and now they want a fair system " , said Venediktov .
#Text=Konstantin Kosachyov , a United Russia parliamentarian , dismissed the concept of discussions with the protest organisers .
#Text=" With all respect for the people who came out to protest , they are not a political party , " he stated .
#Text=Student Daniil Klubov , a leader of the St. Petersburg rally , told the BBC that he does not " belong to any political movement " and is " just a student who is tired of all these lies " .
#Text=Last week , Russian police arrested an estimated 1,600 people after street protests .
#Text=In anticipation of yesterday 's protests , fifty thousand police and riot police were drafted into Moscow .
#Text=Under one hundred arrests were made across the country during the day of protest .
#Text=HAVE YOUR SAY
#Text=Do you believe the Russian elections were fair ?
#Text=Add or view comments

#Text=Television stations operated by the Russian government provided no coverage of protests in Russia from last week 's election , but lifted the blackout one week on , broadcasting images of thousands filling a Moscow park , spilling over a bridge and covering a facing embankment .
#Text=On Friday , Moscow authorities declared an obligatory test for all high school students , scheduling it for the exact time of protests on Saturday ;
#Text=protest leader Alexey Navalny is currently imprisoned by order of a Russian judge .
#Text=And , a Russian health board warned of respiratory diseases being contracted when being in large crowds .
#Text=Russian Ground Forces cautioned that they would be observing , looking for instances of draft evasion as protesters walked through metal detectors .
#Text=Although United Russia were declared victors in last Sunday 's polls , the percentage of votes in their favour decreased significantly — down from 64 % to 49 % .
#Text=In March next year , Putin himself will face voters , seeking a new six-year term as Russian President .
#Text=VoA reported last week that his presidential bid looked likely to succeed ; however , that outcome now seems less predictable .
